frameDefinitions: An Agent or a Cause mentally or physically expends energy rendering an Input, whether implicit or explicit, into a Output.
An Agent expends effort towards achieving a Goal.
An Agent, which may be an individual or group, is engaged in a complex Activity.
These words refer to an Agent joining Parts to form a Whole.
An Agent acts to begin the life of a Process.
frameExamples: Erosion is the <t>work</t> of wind and water on rock.
In addition, our organization will <t>work</t> on improving accountability in every department.
The New Car Assessment <t>Program</t> (NCAP) is dedicated to helping the public buy a safer car.
After discovering her knack for organization, she decided to try to  <t>launch</t> a career in human resources.
listRoleDefinitions: A sentient entity whose physical and mental faculties are directly expended on the <fen>Input</fen> to create the <fen>Output</fen>.
A non-sentient entity whose physical faculties are directly expended on the <fen>Input</fen> to create the <fen>Output</fen>.
The mental or physical faculties onto which the <fen>Agent</fen> or <fen>Cause</fen> expends energy.
The end product, either a concept or physical object onto which the <fen>Agent</fen> or <fen>Cause</fen> has exerted its mental or physical faculties from the rudimentary state of <fen>Input</fen>.
The time at which the <fen>Output</fen> was committed into reality.
The place where the <fen>Output</fen> was birthed.
The <fen>Agent</fen> puts effort into reaching <fen>Goal</fen>.
The <fen>Goal</fen> is what the <fen>Agent</fen> expends effort to achieve.
An entity that is centrally involved in the <fen>Goal</fen> that the <fen>Agent</fen> is attempting to acheive.
This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen> when the effort occurs.
The place where the work is done.
The individual or organization that carries out the project.
An area of human endeavor, typically scientifc in nature, in which the <fen>Agent</fen>'s <fen>Activity</fen> falls.
What the <fen>Agent</fen> (an individual or the members of an organization) are dedicated to doing.
The larger aim that the <fen>Agent</fen> is pursuing by carrying out certain coordinated measures.
An entity (abstract or concrete) which is involved in an implicit <fen>Activity</fen>.
The ongoing plan of action which allows the <fen>Agent</fen> to pursue the <fen>Activity</fen>.
The time at which the <fen>Project</fen> is ongoing.
The location where a <fen>Project</fen> is pursued.

In causative uses of these verbs there is an <fen>Agent</fen> responsible for amalgamating the <fen>Parts</fen>. The <fen>Agent</fen> is generally the External Argument (or the object of a PP-by in passives).
This  role identifies <fen>Whole</fen> as the entity resulting from combination of <fen>Parts</fen>.  When overtly expressed, it is usually a PP Complement (often headed by into).
This role identifies the <fen>Parts</fen> entities being combined, and is often expressed in a single plural NP, usually the direct object of a verb.
This role identifies the first of two <fen>Parts</fen> mentioned. It  is most often the NP-Object of a verb.
This role identifies the second of two <fen>Parts</fen> mentioned. It is usually a PP Complement.
The time at which the amalgamation occurs.
The location that the event occurs.
This Frame Element marks expressions that indicate the process that the <fen>Agent</fen> initiates.
The <fen>Agent</fen> is the actor responsible for starting the <fen>Process</fen>.
This role is for the <fen>Time</fen> when the <fen>Agent</fen> initiates the <fen>Process</fen>.
This role identifies the <fen>Place</fen> where the <fen>Process</fen> is initiated.
